explanation:
- mhd_tool_get_system_cpu_count: the direct caller; needed to determine whether this target implementation is ever invoked (reachability) and how its return value is used (affects whether its operations are semantically relevant).
- mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_special_api_, mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysconf_, mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count, mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysctl_fallback_, mhd_tool_get_sys_cpu_count_sysconf_fallback_: alternative implementations referenced by the caller. Required to see selection logic in the caller (which implementation is chosen under what conditions) to decide if this particular sysctl variant is effectively unused (dead) at link/run time.
- detect_cpu_core_count: higher-level caller in the call chain; needed to determine whether the entire call chain that could reach this function is ever used by the application (global reachability -> dead-code assessment).
- sysctlbyname, sysctl: external system/library functions invoked by this implementation. Their prototypes/behaviour (side effects, error semantics, effects on global state) are necessary to decide whether the calls here produce any observable effect beyond returning a CPU count (i.e. whether removing these calls would change program behaviour).
- __linux__, HAVE_SYSCTLBYNAME, HAVE_SYSCTL, HAS_DECL_CTL_HW, HAS_DECL_HW_NCPUONLINE, HAS_DECL_HW_AVAILCPU: build-time/preprocessor macros that control which portions of this function are compiled. Needed to determine which code actually exists in the compiled unit and thus whether any compiled operations are dead.
- CTL_HW, HW_NCPUONLINE, HW_AVAILCPU: platform constants used to build MIB arrays for sysctl; needed to check conditional compilation and whether the sysctl paths are valid/used on the target platform (affects whether those code blocks are live).

These symbols together let an analyst determine (1) whether the function is ever reachable from program entry points, (2) which portions are compiled in for target builds, and (3) whether the calls inside have observable side effects — all necessary to decide if any executed operations in this function constitute dead code per the MISRA rule.
